        "name": "What is Draft SPARK?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Draft SPARK is a percentile-based scoring model for NCAA Division I college baseball players, built by The Baseball Nerd to project MLB Draft outcomes using only public performance data. It extends the evaluation philosophy of the original SPARK model, built for MiLB and MLB Statcast data, downward to the college level, where Statcast is not publicly available."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How accurate is Draft SPARK at predicting draft outcomes?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Draft SPARK is not designed or marketed as a near-certain predictor. Validated against the 2021-2025 MLB Draft classes, its top-scoring position players land in Round 1 at roughly a 4-5x higher rate than random selection from the same player pool, and its pitcher model shows a comparable lift. Both models' correlation with actual draft position held up, and in the pitcher model's case improved, on the 2026 draft class, which was held out entirely during development as a genuine out-of-sample test."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What data does Draft SPARK use?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Draft SPARK is built entirely on FanGraphs' College Leaderboards, pulled under the No Minimum qualification setting for the 2021 through 2026 seasons, covering over 32,000 batting player-seasons and 31,000 pitching player-seasons. Draft outcome data for backtesting comes from Baseball Almanac's historical MLB Draft archive."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does Draft SPARK adjust for conference strength or strength of schedule?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No, by deliberate design. Testing found that Power Four conference membership predicts a real draft-position advantage independent of on-field performance, but this reflects scouting visibility a player does not control rather than the player's own quality. Draft SPARK scores are conference-blind: two players with identical scores from a major and a mid-major conference are read as equally strong statistical performers."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why doesn't Draft SPARK show a raw numeric score?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "To avoid confusion with the traditional 20-80 scouting grade scale used throughout baseball, where the same numbers carry entirely different meaning. Draft SPARK's public output is always a round-outcome tier (such as Day 1 Priority or Day 2-3 Follow) with within-tier rank, never a raw 0-100 score."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is a two-way player in Draft SPARK?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A player-season qualifies as legitimately two-way only when both the Position Player and Pitcher models' independent reliability floors are cleared in the same season. Draft SPARK further distinguishes an Established two-way player, requiring three or more such qualifying seasons, from incidental single-season dual usage, which the data shows is far more common and not a reliable signal of a genuine dual-threat profile."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How does Draft SPARK relate to the original SPARK Score?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The original SPARK Score evaluates professional players using MiLB and MLB Statcast data. Draft SPARK adapts the same underlying evaluation questions -- skill, trajectory, opportunity, and adjustability -- to NCAA college players, using only publicly available box-score-derived statistics since Statcast data is not public at the college level. Full methodology for the original model is documented in the SPARK Score white paper."
        }
      }
    ]
