    <h1 class="article-title">Draft <em>SPARK</em></h1>
    <p class="article-subtitle">A College Baseball Prospect Scoring Model for the MLB Draft</p>
    <div class="article-meta">
      <div class="meta-author">By <strong>Pete Dwyer</strong> · The Baseball Nerd Analytics Vault</div>
      <div class="meta-pill">11 Sections</div>
      <div class="meta-pill">22,446 Position-Player Seasons Scored</div>
      <div class="meta-pill">19,349 Pitcher Seasons Scored</div>
      <div class="meta-pill">2021–2026 Validated</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="article-body">

  <!-- ABSTRACT -->
  <div class="abstract-box">
    <div class="abstract-label">Abstract</div>
    <p>Draft SPARK is a percentile-based scoring model for NCAA Division I college baseball prospects, extending The Baseball Nerd's SPARK framework, originally built to evaluate professional players using MiLB and MLB Statcast data, to the college level, where Statcast is not publicly available. The model produces two independently validated outputs, a Position Player score and a Pitcher score, each built from a small set of components weighted through a disciplined, bounded-testing process against five years of actual MLB Draft outcomes (2021–2025), with the 2026 draft class held out entirely during development and used only afterward as a genuine out-of-sample check. The top-scoring position players in the validation sample land in Round 1 at roughly a 4–5x higher rate than random selection from the same player pool, and the pitcher model shows a comparable lift; both models held or improved on the 2026 holdout. Several counterintuitive findings from the development process are documented in detail, including a hidden home-run-rate bias in an early version of the pitcher trend component, a validated market discount on pure closer profiles, and a deliberate decision to leave conference strength out of the model entirely despite measurable predictive power.</p>
  </div>

